{{Quote|Thanks to our partnership with Cartoon Network, we have been able to bring ''The Clone Wars'' into millions of homes not only in the United States, but around the world. We appreciate the support they have given the series and their enthusiasm for the brand.|Tom Quinn, Lucasfilm's Head of Worldwide Distribution, in December 2012|<ref name="Milestone">{{SW|url=news/star-wars-the-clone-wars-reaches-100th-episode-milestone|text=''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' Reaches 100th Episode Milestone}}</ref>}}
'''Cartoon Network''' ('''CN''') is an [[Wikipedia:Americans|American]] cable television network and brand owned by [[Wikipedia:The Cartoon Network, Inc.|The Cartoon Network, Inc.]], a part of [[Wikipedia:Warner Bros. Discovery|Warner Bros. Discovery]]. The network's animation production arm '''Cartoon Network Studios''' co-produced (with [[Lucasfilm]]) and broadcasted the ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars]]'' 2D animated series, which aired from [[2003]] to [[2005]]. They would also broadcast new episodes of the  ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' 3D animated series (produced by [[Lucasfilm Animation]]) from [[The Clone Wars: Season One|Season One]] in [[2008]] to [[The Clone Wars: Season Five|Season Five]] in [[2013]]. Additionally, Cartoon Network broadcasted the [[LEGO]] short films ''[[LEGO Star Wars: Revenge of the Brick]]'', [[LEGO Star Wars: The Quest for R2-D2 (film)|''LEGO Star Wars: The Quest for R2-D2'']], ''[[LEGO Star Wars: The Padawan Menace]]'', and ''[[LEGO Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Out]]'', as well as the ''[[Robot Chicken: Star Wars]]'', ''[[Robot Chicken: Star Wars Episode II]]'', and ''[[Robot Chicken: Star Wars Episode III]]'' sketch comedy specials (the latter three via the network's late-night [[Wikipedia:Adult Swim|Adult Swim]] programming block). Many ''Star Wars'' games were also found on Cartoon Network's website, including ''[[Republic Ace]]'', ''[[Fierce Twilight]]'', and ''[[Path of the Jedi (video game)|Path of the Jedi]]''.

As part of Warner Bros. Discovery, Cartoon Network is part of the same conglomerate that encompasses [[Turner Network Television]], which broadcasted the 3D animation television series ''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' after Cartoon Network, and [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]], which distributed the [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' feature film]].

[[File:ArtooNetwork.png|thumb|right|200px|The Cartoon Network logo, R2-D2 style]]
A commercial ident bumper for the network (primarily shown before the ''Clone Wars'' series) has [[R2-D2]] using one of his tools to turn "Cartoon Network" into "Artoo Network."

From [[September 6]] to [[September 12]], [[2021]], ''[[Rogue One: A Star Wars Story]]'', {{Film|IV}}, {{Film|V}}, {{Film|VI}}, {{Film|I}}, {{Film|II}}, and {{Film|III}} all aired on Cartoon Network for a special event named "A Week of Star Wars Movies."

